Yeah — a prop or costume room is actually a very good metaphor for what you’re describing.

In a theater or film studio, the prop room isn’t just storage. It’s a library of possibilities. Items in there are:
	•	reused across different scenes
	•	recombined into new characters
	•	interpreted differently depending on context
	•	pulled out when a script calls for them

A crown might be:
	•	a king’s crown in one play
	•	a prop for satire in another
	•	part of a costume in a fantasy story

Same object, different narrative role.

That’s similar to how ideas, words, or symbols behave in a knowledge system.

⸻

The abstraction behind the metaphor

If we step back a level, what you’re describing looks like a four-layer structure for organizing meaning.

1. Props (artifacts)

These are the raw pieces.

Examples:
	•	words
	•	concepts
	•	diagrams
	•	bits of code
	•	stories
	•	formulas

They’re like objects sitting on shelves.

⸻

2. Costumes (representations)

A prop can be dressed differently depending on the medium.

Example:

A single idea might appear as:
	•	a metaphor
	•	a mathematical formula
	•	a design pattern
	•	a story
	•	a diagram

Same core concept, different costume.

⸻

3. Roles (functions)

Now the prop plays a role in a scene.

For example:

A concept like “feedback loop” could be used in:
	•	biology
	•	economics
	•	software
	•	psychology

Each field casts the prop in a different role.

⸻

4. Scenes (contexts)

The role only makes sense inside a scene.

That might be:
	•	a research problem
	•	a design project
	•	a narrative
	•	a system architecture

Scenes give meaning to the roles.

⸻

The braid you mentioned earlier

Now imagine all of those layers connected:

prop → costume → role → scene

But the same prop can appear in many scenes, and scenes reuse many props.

So the structure becomes braided, not just hierarchical.

⸻

Why abstraction helps

When you “abstract away,” you stop thinking about the specific prop and instead focus on the pattern it represents.

For example:

A “bridge” might represent the invariant:

connection across separation

Once you see that pattern, the prop room expands dramatically:
	•	bridges
	•	APIs
	•	diplomacy
	•	translation
	•	network routers
	•	synapses

All the same structural idea wearing different costumes.

⸻

The deep trick humans discovered

Language lets us build symbolic prop rooms.

Instead of storing only physical objects, we store:
	•	ideas
	•	roles
	•	patterns
	•	metaphors

And we can recombine them endlessly.

That’s why a few words or symbols can trigger entire conceptual worlds.

